===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
{{Han compound|大|t1=man|口|t2=mouth, object|ls=ic}}. Top figure simplified to {{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|土}}, unrelated to {{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|士||scholar, gentleman}}, while bottom simplified to {{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|厶}}; a conservative variant is [[厺]].

There are various interpretations of the combination of “man” and “mouth, object”. One is that the ideograph represented a man with a hole marked in his crotch, with the idea of “anus” (i.e. getting rid of) ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}). Another is that it represented a man ''departing'' from a cave or city.

Alternatively, it may be the original character of {{och-l|呿|to open one's mouth}}, the meaning given by the combination of {{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|大||big}} and {{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|口||mouth}}. The meaning “to depart” would be an extension of the meaning “to open one's mouth”, as the lips ''depart'' from each other when one's mouth is open.

{{w|Shuowen Jiezi}} interprets the character as a {{Han compound|大|𠙴|t1=man|c1=s|c2=p|ls=psc|nocap=1}}.

In addition, {{lang|zh|去}} is also the original character of {{och-l|盍|gloss=to cover}}. The {{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|大}} could be a cover on top of an object {{l-lite|zh|sc=Hani|口}}.

The man on top is simplified as 土 as in [[赤]] and [[走]] (< [[𧺆]]).

===Etymology===
There were two pronunciations in Middle Chinese. The [[rising tone]] pronunciation originally meant “to put away, to eliminate” (causative of “to go away”), and the falling tone “to go away, to leave, to depart” (anticausative). The merger of the two pronunciations already happened in Old Chinese and most extant dialects do not observe this distinction now.

This word is of Sino-Tibetan origin with the basic meaning of "to get rid of". Compare {{cog|bo|སྐྱག||to spend, to lay out; dung, excrement}}, {{m|bo|རྐྱག||dirt, excrement}}, {{cog|my|ကျ||to fall, to become low}}, {{m|my|ချ||to put down, to bring down, to lower}}.

